      <tr><td colspan=1  style='font-size: 9.5px;'>39 threads, <a href=item.html?item=6322&start=0>1</a> <a href=item.html?item=6322&start=25>2</a>  page(s) long</td><td  style='font-size: 9.5px;' align=right>&nbsp;<a href=item.html?item=6322&start=25>Next Page</a></td></tr></table></form><ul><table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=102963166662748></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f102963166662748><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=item.html?item=6322&mid=102963166662748>Rolling on this item?</a> <a id=fs8 href=item.html?item=6322&mid=102963166662748#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=43695><span id=Sage>Argfeld</span></a>, <span id=Sage>Sage</span><br><span id=notbold>56 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Sat, Aug 17th 8:59 PM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[5.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Hmmm.&nbsp;&nbsp;There are some reasonably high level guilds that divide loot by random rolling, but guilds that use this method don't tend to power up very quickly, because gear ends up going to people who can't make optimal use of it.  A guild that relied on random rolls for everything and was formed the day that EQ was first released might only now be getting to the point that they could acquire this item.  Random rolls also tend to anger people quite a bit when someone who really shouldn't have gotten a certain item just gets lucky.  This makes it hard for such a guild to keep members.  The only reason my guild would random roll for such an item would be if the officers in charge of loot could not decide which of a small number of guild members (2 or 3 for example) would be best to give the item to.  Random rolling for loot rarely lasts very long once a guild goes planar.<br><br>The most likely choice for who gets this item the very first time a guild comes across it is a monk, for reasons which others have already made abundantly clear (some in a rather aggressive manner).  As the guild gets more and more of these, other classes will certainly get them as well.  Typically though, by the time less ideal classes would get their turn at this item, they will have already gotten a comparable (or better)item somewhere else.  I see this happen quite often.  When an item is out of reach, everyone that can use it wants it.  By the time a guild is able to actually get it, most of the ones that used to want it have gotten something better or are close to getting something better.  They might actually turn up their nose at the item they used to drool over.  I actually used to want Velious quest gear, until I got better.  To this date, I have never had a single piece of Velious quest gear and now I don't want any.<br><br>If perchance the guild that gets this item uses a DKP system, then the odds of someone besides a monk getting it the first time it drops are higher, but if I had to bet money on who would get it, I would still say that a monk was most probable because he would have the most motivation and because monks tend to build up more points than other classes because there is so little for them to spend points on.  How's that for a run-on sentence?<br><br>It is not a law of nature that &quot;monk items&quot; always go to monks.  Unless it explicity says that only monks can use it, there is always a chance that it will go elsewhere.  If it does go elsewhere, then it's no big deal.  If your guild can get this item once, then they can get it two times or three or four or however many times they want to.  Your turn will come.<br><br>Even if this item were the ultimate &quot;monk item&quot; and my guild instead awarded it to a druid, for example, I would certainly not leave my guild as I rather like being in OSW.  Leaving a guild over a bad loot decision is a mistake, unless your guild has a serious, chronic problem with making such decisions.  If you do leave your guild over a loot decision, you will probably not be missed.  I think some people are just fond of using the expression, &quot;I'd leave my guild if item X got awarded to class Y!&quot;, even if they really wouldn't do such a thing.  <br><br>If you are in a guild capable of getting this item, they almost certainly have a very effective way of determining who will get it.  Your opinion about who should get this item in such a circumstance probably doesn't mean diddly-squat unless you are one of the people in charge of loot allocation.  So basically, arguing over whether this is a monk item or a ranger item or whatever is a complete and utter waste of time.  <br><br>I think that most of us would instead like to see information about how to get this item, strategies for killing the monster that drops it, getting to the monster that drops it, etc.  Also, if an item has a specific use, it would be interesting to know any little &quot;tricks&quot; that can be done with the item to make an individual or a group or a raid more effective.  <br><br>If you are not even close to being able to get this quality of item, you really shouldn't be ranting about who should or should not get it.  Most of the rants I see about level 60 equipment are made by people below level 40.  What do they know about high level loot allocation?  Odds are that there are facets of the game at the level required to get this item that most people are not aware of yet.  The person whose opinion you criticize may know a heck of a lot more about this item and who should wear it than you do.  I don't post about Vex Thal loot because my guild is not quite up to that level of the game yet. I feel comfortable posting about this because my guild has been after North ToV loot for quite a while now.  I'm even wearing some at the moment.<br><br>Argfeld<br>Level 58 Monk<br>Order of the Scattered Winds<br>Bertoxxulous<br>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
